      "writtenOn": "2017-08-23T18:56:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "rx is a commit hash, r.Next is cursor, which isn\u0027t necessarily a commit hash.\n\nin practice, gitiles currently uses a commit hash as a cursor, however if there are merge commits, next call would be missing commits. For example, consider this history:\n\nr0 -\u003e r1 -----\u003e r3 --\u003e r4 --\u003e r6\n         \\                  /\n          r2 -----------\u003e r5 \n\n# note, I assigned i for each r_i based on topological sort and for (r2, r3) and (r4, r5) based on their timestamps.\n\nNow, suppose page size is 2, and we want LogForward(r0, r6, limit\u003d3).\nThen first rawLog(r0..r6) will return [r6, r5], next\u003dr4,\n\u003d\u003e rawLog(r0..r4) which returns [r4, r3], next\u003dr1   # And we lost r2!\n\u003d\u003e rawLog(r0..r1) which returns [r1]   # AFAIU, r0 won\u0027t be returend at all, and I think LogForward right now won\u0027t return r0 either.\n\nTo conclude, I think the only consistently right way to do this is to use gitiles paging cursor directly here as a cursor, not assuming it to be a commit, which means LogForward can\u0027t piggy back on rawLog as is.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 221,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 221,
        "endChar": 13
      },
